SIMPLE: prophet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prophet
<hw>Proph"et</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>proph⟦egrave⟧te</ets>, L. <ets>propheta</ets>, fr. Gr. <?/,
literally, one who speaks for another, especially, one who speaks for a
god an interprets his will to man, fr. <?/ to say beforehand; <?/ for,
before + <?/ to say or speak. See <er>Fame</er>. ]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who prophesies, or foretells events; a
predicter; a foreteller.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One inspired or instructed by God to speak in his
name, or announce future events, <as>as, Moses, Elijah,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An interpreter; a spokesman.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Ex. vii. 1.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A mantis.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>School of the prophets</b></col> <fld>(Anc. Jewish
Hist.)</fld>, <cd>a school or college in which young men were educated
and trained for public teachers or members of the prophetic order. These
students were called <xex>sons of the prophets</xex>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prophetess</ent>⟦br⟧
